==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prelate
<hw>Prel"ate</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧lat</ets>, LL. <ets>praelatus</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>praelatus</ets>, used as p. p. of <ets>praeferre</ets> to prefer,
but from a different root. See <er>Elate</er>.]</ety> <def>A clergyman
of a superior order, as an archbishop or a bishop, having authority over
the lower clergy; a dignitary of the church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word and the words derived from it are often used
invidiously, in English ecclesiastical history, by dissenters,
respecting the Established Church system.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hear him but reason in divinity, . . . ⟦br⟧
You would desire the king were made a <qex>prelate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prelate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prelate
<hw>Prel"ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To act as a
prelate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Right <qex>prelating</qex> is busy laboring, and not lording.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prelateity</ent>⟦br⟧
